 [[Burley, Idaho]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Kathy Simpson\n|education    = [[Utah State University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[Washington University in St. Louis]] ([[Doctor of Dental Medicine|DMD]])\n|website      = {{url|simpson.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Michael Keith Simpson''' (born September 8, 1950) is an American politician serving as a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]], representing {{ushr|Idaho|2|}}. First elected in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1998|1998 elections]], he is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and previously served in the [[Idaho House of Representatives]] (1984\u20131998). He was the House's [[List of Speakers of the Idaho House of Representatives|38th Speaker]] from 1992 to 1998.\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nBorn in [[Burley, Idaho|Burley]], Simpson was raised in [[Blackfoot, Idaho|Blackfoot]], where his father was a [[dentist]]. He graduated from [[Blackfoot High School]] in 1968, [[Utah State University]] in [[Logan, Utah|Logan]] in 1972, and the [[Washington University School of Dental Medicine]]<ref>The Washington University School of Dental Medicine, 1866-1991 http://beckerexhibits.wustl.edu/dental/history/index.html</ref> in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], in 1977.<ref name=ocd2011>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fVSkbYQp6qgC&pg=PA83&lpg=PA83#v=onepage&q&f=false|publisher=United States Congress|title=Official Congressional Directory, 2011-2012: 112th Congress |year=2011|page=83}}</ref> Simpson practiced dentistry in Blackfoot until his election to [[United States House of Representatives|Congress]] in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1998#Idaho|1998]]. He was elected to the Blackfoot City Council in 1980 and was elected to the [[Idaho Legislature|state legislature]] in 1984, the first of seven terms. He was the [[Speaker (politics)|Speaker]] of the [[Idaho House of Representatives|Idaho House]] prior to his election to Congress.\n\nWhile some members of Congress with a medical background prefer to be addressed as \"Doctor\" (most notably former [[Senate Majority Leader]] [[Bill Frist]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0309/20181.html|title=Honorable? Former lawmakers mull title \u2013 Daniel Libit |publisher=Politico.Com|accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> Simpson does not insist that he be referred to as Dr. Simpson, preferring to simply go by Congressman or Mr. Simpson.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\nWhile the Republican Party held the majority in the U.S. House of Representatives, Simpson often served as the [[Speaker Pro Tempore]] of the House, particularly during debates concerning controversial legislation, due to his command of House procedure. Simpson is known to have broken several sounding boards with the gavel while calling the House to order.  This inspired Simpson to have a number of sounding boards produced in Idaho, which he presented to then Speaker of the House [[Dennis Hastert]] (R-IL) as a joke.  When the Republican Party regained control of the House of Representatives in 2010, Mr. Simpson began once again to serve frequently as the Speaker Pro Tempore of the House.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/congressional-record/2017/03/07/house-section/article/H1539-2|title=Congressional Record|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/congressional-record/2017/4/8/house-section/article/h2795-3?r=22|title=Congressional Record|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n\n====2013 government shutdown====\nIn October 2013, Simpson voted to end the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]].<ref name=\"King\">{{cite news|last=King|first=Neil Jr.|title=Idaho Race Shows Split in Republican Donor Base|url=https://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303332904579226231084993234?mod=ITP_pageone_1|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=2013-11-29}}</ref>\n\n==== Health care ====\n\n;Affordable Care Act repeal \nHe voted for and presided<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/boise/2017/may/04/us-house-passes-gop-health-care-bill-simpson-labrador-both-support-it/|title=U.S. House passes GOP health care bill; Simpson, Labrador both support it|work=Spokesman.com|access-date=2017-05-04|language=en}}</ref> over the vote for the [[American Health Care Act of 2017]] which passed the House May 4, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2017/roll256.xml|title=FINAL VOTE RESULTS FOR ROLL CALL 256|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n;Newborn health\nSimpson was an original co-sponsor of the [[Newborn Screening Saves Lives Reauthorization Act of 2013 (H.R. 1281; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would amend the [[Public Health Service Act]] to [[authorization bill|reauthorize]] grant programs and other initiatives to promote expanded [[newborn screening|screening of newborns]] and children for heritable disorders.<ref name=cbo1281>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 1281|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45434|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref> Simpson said that \"the bill reflects the realities of reduced budgets Washington, but continues and strengthens the well established system of monitoring and evaluating infant conditions soon after birth. Just one small blood sample from the newborn's foot identifies infants with genetic or other conditions that can be treated quickly and effectively, saving and improving thousands of lives.\"<ref name=RoyPR22>{{cite web|title=Rep. Roybal-Allard and Rep. Simpson introduce the Newborn Screening Saves Lives Authorization Act|url=http://roybal-allard.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=325195|publisher=House Office of Rep. Roybal-Allard|accessdate=24 June 2014|date=22 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n==== Energy and water ====\n\nOn June 20, 2014, Simpson introduced the [[Energy and Water Development and Related Agencies Appropriations Act, 2015 (H.R. 4923; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would make [[appropriations bill (United States)|appropriations]] for energy and water development and related agencies for FY2015.<ref name=4923sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4923 \u2013 Summary|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4923|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> The bill would appropriate $34 billion, which is only $50 million less than these agencies currently receive.<ref name=HillThisWeek7>{{cite news|last1=Marcos|first1=Cristina|title=This week: Sportsmen's bill, appropriations|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/scheduling/211332-this-week-appropriations-sportsmens-bill|accessdate=10 July 2014|publisher=The Hill|date=7 July 2014}}</ref> The appropriations for the [[United States Department of Energy]] and the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] are made by this bill.\n\n====Gun rights====\nHe voted for and helped to pass the \"National Right-to-Carry Reciprocity Act of 2011\".<ref>http://www.vote-smart.org/bill/14168/37348/2917/national-right-to-carry-reciprocity-act-of-2011{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Under this new law, which passed through the House of Representatives on November 16, 2011, people with a valid license are allowed to carry a concealed weapon in other states, as long as those states allow concealed weapons and don't have specific rules about concealed weapons carried by nonresidents.<ref>See http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/192457-gop-looking-to-ease-concealed-weapons-rules-next-week</ref>\n\n====Idaho-focused environmental legislation====\nSimpson's hallmark legislation in the House of Representatives has been the Central Idaho Economic Development and Recreation Act (CIEDRA), which would create 312,000 acres of wilderness in central Idaho, much of which is currently a wilderness study area.  Simpson has faced substantial resistance from groups like the Sierra Club who claim the bill lacks \"wilderness values\"<ref name=\"idaho.sierraclub.org\">{{cite web|url=http://idaho.sierraclub.org/sawtooth/issues/CIEDRA/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-05-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ENw38Jtb?url=http://idaho.sierraclub.org/sawtooth/issues/CIEDRA/index.html |archivedate=2013-02-12 |df= }}</ref> because the bill allows for motorized access to certain portions of the wilderness area and some federal land would be transferred to the State of Idaho to promote the economic development of the local community and the recreational use of National Forest land and other public lands in central Idaho.<ref>See http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h109-3603</ref> Simpson has also faced opposition from groups who oppose new federal land designations, and wilderness designations particularly because of restricted access to wilderness areas.<ref name=\"idaho.sierraclub.org\"/> In August 2015 a revised version of CIEDRA, the Sawtooth National Recreation Area and Jerry Peak Wilderness Additions Act, passed Congress and was signed by President Obama, creating the [[Hemingway\u2013Boulders Wilderness|Hemingway\u2013Boulders]], [[Jim McClure\u2013Jerry Peak Wilderness|Jim McClure\u2013Jerry Peak]], and [[White Clouds Wilderness|White Clouds]] wilderness areas, which cover a total of {{convert|275665|acre|ha}} of central Idaho.<ref>{{cite news|first=Rich |last=Landers |title=Obama signs Boulder-White Clouds Wilderness Bill |newspaper=The Spokesman-Review |date=August 7, 2015 |url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/outdoors/2015/aug/07/obama-signs-boulder-white-clouds-wilderness-bill/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ac7HrrFv?url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/outdoors/2015/aug/07/obama-signs-boulder-white-clouds-wilderness-bill/ |archivedate=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2015 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, 2014, Simpson introduced the bill [[To amend the Wild and Scenic Rivers Act to authorize the Secretary of the Interior to maintain or replace certain facilities and structures for commercial recreation services at Smith Gulch in Idaho (H.R. 4283; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=4238allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4238 \u2013 All Actions|url=https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4283/all-actions|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> The bill would require the [[United States Secretary of Agriculture]] to permit private entities to repair or replace certain commercial facilities on [[United States Forest Service]] land in [[Idaho]].<ref name=cbo4283>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4283|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45517|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref> Simpson said that \"this legislation clarifies Congress' intent of the 2004 amendments to the Wild and Scenic Rivers Act which continued the existing use and occupancy of commercial services in this corridor of the Salmon River\".<ref name=SimpsonPR>{{cite web|title=Simpson Bill to Authorize Facilities Maintenance on Salmon River Passes House|url=http://simpson.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=392777|publisher=House Office of Rep. Mike Simpson|accessdate=9 September 2014|date=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Judgeship reorganization===\nHe also played a crucial role with the [[Ninth Circuit]] Court of Appeals Judgeship and Reorganization Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maplight.org/map/us/bill/11026/default/history |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120904091402/http://www.maplight.org/map/us/bill/11026/default/history |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2012-09-04 |title=Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals Judgeship and Reorganization Act of 2007 \u2013 Vote: Referred to the House Committee on the Judiciary. &#124; History and Status &#124; MAPLight.org \u2013 Money and Politics |publisher=MAPLight.org |date=2008-12-31 |accessdate=2010-08-23 }}</ref> Mike Simpson's goal is to amend [[title 28]], and create the appointment of additional [[Federal Circuit]] Judges, to divide the [[Ninth Judicial Circuit]] into two smaller judicial circuits.<ref>See http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h112-162&tab=committees</ref> The Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals Judgeship and Reorganization Act was introduced to House Judiciary Committee, and more specifically to the subcommittee on Courts and Competition Policy. Since Jan 24, 2011, the bill has been in the subcommittee, where it will be refined before being presented to the Judiciary Committee, then later the actual House of Representatives.\n\n=== Methamphetamine ===\nFollowing the death of Congressman [[Charlie Norwood]] (R-GA) in February, 2007, Simpson has become a leading advocate of the [[American Dental Association]] (ADA) in Congress, in part because his profession is dentistry. The advocacy inspired Simpson to introduce legislation regarding [[methamphetamine]], specifically how the drug affects tooth decay or \"[[methmouth]]\". The bill is formally called H.R. 1671: Meth Mouth Prevention and Community Recovery Act, with the purpose to understand and address the [[oral health]] problems associated with methamphetamine. The bill's goals are to expand and intensify the [[Department of Health and Human Services]], make grants available to educate 12- to 17-year-olds about methmouth, and to promote a series of education activities for all dentists to learn about substance use disorders and their relationship to [[oral health]] and the provision of dental care.<ref>See {{cite web |url=http://www.house.gov/list/press/id02_simpson/meth_mouth.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-11-22 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504232512/http://www.house.gov/list/press/id02_simpson/meth_mouth.html |archivedate=2009-05-04 |df= }}</ref> As of March 24, 2009, the bill was put from the [[House Committee on Energy and Commerce]] to the [[Subcommittee on Health]] where it has been debated, but never brought to a conclusion. As soon as that happens, it will be brought up before the whole committee, then later the House of Representatives.<ref>See http://www.govtrack.us/congress/bill.xpd?bill=h111-1671</ref>\n\n=== Tax reform ===\n\nSimpson voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=27 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref> After passing the bill, Simpson said he spoke to Idaho farmers, ranchers and businesses who called for a simplified tax code and reform. He says the bill will \"create economic growth in the United States by unleashing American small businesses and unburdening middle class families so they can make better financial decisions with their own money.\"<ref name=\"Russell121917\">{{cite web|last1=Russell|first1=Betsy Z.|title=Labrador, Simpson laud GOP tax bill as it passes House|url=http://www.spokesman.com/blogs/boise/2017/dec/19/labrador-simpson-laud-gop-tax-bill-it-passes-house/|website=Spokesman.com|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n** [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Energy and Water Development|Subcommittee on Energy and Water Development]]\n** [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies]] (Chairman)\n** [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education, and Related Agencies]]\n\n===Party leadership===\n* House Republican Steering Committee\n\n===Caucus membership===\n{|\n|\n* House Potato Caucus \u2013 Co-Chair\n* House Sugar Caucus \u2013 Co-Chair\n* Oral Health Caucus \u2013 Co-Chair\n* Congressional TRIO Caucus \u2013 Co-Chair\n*[[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref>\n* Nuclear Cleanup Caucus\n|\n* House Bio-fuels Caucus\n* Congressional Sportsmen Caucus\n* Mining Caucus\n* Immigration Reform Caucus\n*[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> \n* Renewable Energy Caucus\n|\n* Congressional Native American Caucus\n* House Rural Health Coalition\n* Caucus to Fight and Control Meth\n* 2nd Amendment Caucus\n* Congressional Taiwan Caucus\n* [[Republican Main Street Partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://republicanmainstreet.org/members/|format=|publisher=Republican Mains Street Partnership|date=|accessdate=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n|\n*[[Afterschool Caucuses]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/policyCongressionalCaucuses.cfm|format=|publisher=Afterschool Alliance|date=|accessdate=17 April 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref> \n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n|}\nIn the [[111th United States Congress]] Simpson became the [[Ranking Member]] on the Interior, Environment, and Related Agencies Appropriations Subcommittee. Upon assuming this position, and the subsequent chairmanship of the subcommittee, he is considered a \"Cardinal\" (a term applied to the chairmen or ranking members of the Appropriations Subcommittees) within the House Republican Caucus. He also serves as the small state representative on the 33-member House Republican Steering Committee.<ref name=\"thehill1\">{{cite web|url=http://briefingroom.thehill.com/2008/11/25/simpson-replaces-young-on-gop-steering-committee |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130204104739/http://briefingroom.thehill.com/2008/11/25/simpson-replaces-young-on-gop-steering-committee |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2013-02-04 |title=Blog Briefing Room \u2013 The Hill's Blog Briefing Room |publisher=Briefingroom.thehill.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23 }}</ref> Known as the \"committee of committees\", the Steering Committee decides which Republican lawmakers become ranking members on House committees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://briefingroom.thehill.com/2008/11/25/simpson-replaces-young-on-gop-steering-committee/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120708150416/http://briefingroom.thehill.com/2008/11/25/simpson-replaces-young-on-gop-steering-committee/ |dead-url=yes |archive-date=2012-07-08 |title=Blog Briefing Room \u2013 The Hill's Blog Briefing Room |publisher=Briefingroom.thehill.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23 }}</ref> Simpson replaced Congressman [[Don Young]] (R-AK) on the committee.<ref name=\"thehill1\"/>\n\n== Political positions ==\nSimpson is a member of the Republican Party. However, he is known to be pragmatic on certain issues. For example, he was one of a handful of Republicans to vote in favor of the reauthorization of the [[State Children's Health Insurance Program]] (SCHIP) in the 110th Congress.<ref>http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2007/roll1009.xml</ref> He has also been a supporter of the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] and the [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], voting each year against Republican amendments to strip them of funding. In the past, he has opposed \"[[Earmark (politics)|earmarks]]\", or congressionally directed spending.\n\n''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'' listed Simpson as one of the 10 Best Members of Congress in October 2008.<ref name=\"esquire1\">{{cite web|last=David |first=Elliott |url=http://www.esquire.com/features/esquire-endorsements-2008/10-best-members-congress-text?click=main_sr |title=10 Best Members of Congress \u2013 Election 2008 |publisher=Esquire |date=2008-10-15 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> The magazine said of Simpson, \"More than any other representative, Simpson lives by the philosophy that democratic representation is a matter of finding not advantageous positions but common ground...\"<ref name=\"esquire1\"/> The magazine's portrayal of Simpson echoes one of his personal philosophies, which is embodied in a quote by [[Henry Clay]]: \"Politics is not about ideological purity or moral self-righteousness. It is about governing, and if a politician cannot compromise he cannot govern effectively.\" This quote is framed and hangs in Simpson's Washington D.C. office.<ref>See http://www.hcn.org/issues/338/16795</ref> Simpson played a key role in the election of [[John Boehner]] (R-OH) to the position of [[House Majority Leader]] in the [[109th United States Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idahostatesman.com/207/story/14316.html |title=Ties to House leader pay off for Simpson, Idaho &#124; Dan Popkey's reporting and columns |publisher=Idaho Statesman |date=2006-10-13 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n=== Domestic issues ===\n\n==== Farming ====\n\nSimpson is a strong supporter of the domestic [[sugar beet]] producers,<ref>[http://www.sugaralliance.org/newsroom/reps-melancon-and-simpson-named-house-sugar-caucus-chairs.html]{{dead link|date=August 2010}}</ref> and the Idaho potato growers.<ref>See {{cite web |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/244/story/35363.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-03-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090109141538/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/244/story/35363.html |archivedate=2009-01-09 |df= }}</ref> In 2010, Simpson took up the cause, alongside his former Democratic colleague, [[Walt Minnick]], the lead sponsor of the bill, to secure a third federal judge for Idaho.<ref name=\"idahoreporter.com\">http://www.idahoreporter.com/2010/minnick-and-simpson-working-on-getting-idaho-a-third-federal-judge/</ref> Simpson was quoted as saying, \"The caseload of the Idaho District Court has increased significantly in recent decades resulting in Idaho's district judges carrying a disproportionate share of cases in relation to their colleagues in other states.\"<ref name=\"idahoreporter.com\"/>\n\n==== Gun law ====\nSimpson was one of the Members of Congress to sign the [[D.C. v. Heller]] amicus brief which supported a recognition of the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] as an individual right.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abanet.org/publiced/preview/briefs/pdfs/07-08/07-290_RespondentAmCuSenateHouseMembers.pdf |title=Brief of respondent for District of Columbia v. Heller, 07-290 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==== Health care ====\n\nSimpson has is committed to repealing the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]], questioning its constitutionality and effectiveness.<ref>''See'' http://www.idahostatejournal.com/news/local/article_66f4c33a-43ff-11df-aaa4-001cc4c002e0.html</ref>  He is close to and loyal to Speaker [[John Boehner]].<ref>Jake Sherman and John Bresnahan (20 December 2012), [http://www.politico.com/story/2012/12/john-boehners-plan-b-toughest-hour-85391_Page2.html Boehner\u2019s toughest hour] ''[[Politico]]''</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.idahostatesman.com/speaker-boehner-to-host-50-boise-lunch-for-congressman-simpson/|title=Speaker Boehner to host $50 Boise lunch for Congressman Simpson \u00bb Idaho Statesman Blogs|website=blogs.idahostatesman.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/USA/Politics/Politics-Voices/2015/0903/How-Mike-Simpson-s-triumph-for-wilderness-was-a-triumph-for-Congress|title=How Mike Simpson's triumph for wilderness was a triumph for Congress|last=Feehery|first=John|date=2015-09-03|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2017-04-12|issn=0882-7729}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lmtribune.com/northwest/former-u-s-speaker-stops-in-lewiston/article_59750d61-7b71-5d86-8698-0674932b30b6.html|title=Former U.S. speaker stops in Lewiston|last=TRIBUNE|work=The Lewiston Tribune|access-date=2017-04-12|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.com/e/brunch-with-fmr-speaker-john-boehner-in-boise-tickets-26843205751|title=Brunch with Fmr Speaker John Boehner in Boise!|website=Eventbrite|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Economic issues ===\n\n====Corporations====\nSimpson supports an agenda of low taxes and pro-business policies.<ref>[http://www.idahostatesman.com/idahopolitics/story/508538.html Idaho Statesman]</ref>\n\n====Tax reform====\nSimpson supports tax reform.<ref name=\"Almukhtar\" /> When asked about the [[Grover Norquist#Taxpayer Protection Pledge|Grover Norquist pledge]] to oppose any net increase in taxes, Simpson said, \"Well, first the pledge: I signed that in 1998 when I first ran. I didn't know I was signing a marriage agreement that would last forever.\"<ref>{{YouTube|HFWRvZcRe08|Fox News}}</ref>\n\n=== International issues ===\n\n====Energy====\nSimpson is also known as an outspoken proponent of [[nuclear power]], extolling its virtues as an environmentally friendly source of energy with minimal carbon output. Simpson's support for this form of energy plays a significant role in his membership of the [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Energy and Water Development]], which oversees the [[Idaho National Laboratory]], a main site for nuclear and [[alternative energy]] research in the United States.\n\n===Social issues===\n\nSimpson supports efforts to make it illegal to desecrate the [[American flag]].<ref name=\"OTICivilRights\"/>\n\n==== Abortion ====\n\nSimpson is [[pro-life]]. He has a zero rating from [[NARAL Pro-Choice America]] and a 100% rating from the [[National Right to Life Committee]] for his voting record regarding [[abortion]]. He opposes using federal monies to fund abortions, [[embryonic stem cell]] research, restricting the transport of minors over state lines to receive abortions, [[partial-birth abortion]]s except to save a mother's life and [[human cloning]]. He supports cutting federal funding from [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\"OTIAbortion\">{{cite web|title=Mike Simpson on Abortion|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Mike_Simpson_Abortion.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Affirmative action====\n\nSimpson has a 28 percent rating from the [[NAACP]] for his [[affirmative action]]-related voting record.<ref name=\"OTICivilRights\"/>\n\n==== Cannabis ====\n\nSimpson has a \"D\" rating from [[NORML]] for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related causes. Simpson is opposed to veterans having access to medical marijuana if recommended by their [[Veterans Health Administration]] doctor and if it is legal for medicinal purposes in their state of residence.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Idaho Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/idaho|website=NORML|accessdate=27 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\n====Civil rights====\n\nSimpson has a 13 percent rating from the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] for his civil rights voting record.<ref name=\"OTICivilRights\"/>\n\n==== LGBT ====\nSimpson has a zero score from the [[Human Rights Campaign]] regarding his [[LGBT]] voting record. He opposes [[same-sex marriage]] and supports prohibiting gay adoptions in Washington, DC.<ref name=\"OTICivilRights\">{{cite web|title=Mike Simpson on Civil Rights|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/House/Mike_Simpson_Civil_Rights.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=27 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Political Campaigns==\nSimpson entered the 1998 campaign for the U.S. House seat vacated by [[Mike Crapo]], who was running for [[United States Senate]]. He defeated former [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] Congressman [[Richard H. Stallings]] in the general election. Simpson did not face serious opposition in 2002 and 2004. In 2006 Simpson defeated former Democratic state representative [[Jim D. Hansen]], son of former Republican Congressman [[Orval H. Hansen]], to win reelection.\n\n===2008===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2008#District 2}}\nSimpson defeated two primary challengers winning with 85.2% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/results/2008/Primary/tot_stwd.htm |title=2008 Primary Results statewide |website=www.sos.idaho.gov |access-date=2017-04-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090416030919/http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/RESULTS/2008/Primary/tot_stwd.htm |archivedate=2009-04-16 |df= }}</ref>\n\nSimpson defeated Democrat [[Debbie Holmes]] with 71% of the vote.<ref>[http://www.sos.idaho.gov/ELECT/results/ENR/statewide_total.html 2008 results] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220000000/http://www.sos.idaho.gov/ELECT/results/ENR/statewide_total.html |date=February 20, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2008 Presidential primaries, Simpson was an early supporter of former Massachusetts Governor [[Mitt Romney]] and a member of his Congressional Whip Team.<ref>http://www.politicalbase.com/people/mitt-romney/14237/supporters/</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=pb |url=http://2008romney.blogspot.com/2007/02/whip-team-for-mitt-romney.html |title=Mitt Romney 2008: Whip Team for Mitt Romney |publisher=2008romney.blogspot.com |date=2007-02-06 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2010#District 2}}\nIn the Republican primary, Simpson defeated [[Chick Heileson]] of Iona and Russ Mathews of Idaho Falls.\n\nSimpson defeated Democratic nominee Mike Crawford and Independent candidate Brian Schad with 68.8% of the vote.\n\n===2012===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2012#District 2}}\nIn the Republican primary, Simpson defeated [[Chick Helieson]] with 69.6% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/results/2012/Primary/tot_stwd.htm|title=2012 Primary Results statewide|website=www.sos.idaho.gov|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref>\n\nSimpson defeated Democratic nominee [[Nicole LeFavour]] with 65.1% of the vote.<ref name=\"Statewide Totals\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/results/2014/General/statewide_totals.html |title=Statewide Totals |website=www.sos.idaho.gov |access-date=2017-04-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141201002048/http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/RESULTS/2014/General/statewide_totals.html |archivedate=2014-12-01 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===2014===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2014#District 2}}\nIn the Republican primary, Simpson defeated lawyer [[Bryan Smith (US Politician)|Bryan Smith]], earning 61.8% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/results/2014/Primary/statewide_totals.html |title=Statewide Totals |website=www.sos.idaho.gov |access-date=2017-04-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140728081413/http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/RESULTS/2014/Primary/statewide_totals.html |archivedate=2014-07-28 |df= }}</ref>\n\nSimpson defeated former congressman [[Richard H. Stallings]] in the general election, earning 61.4% of the vote.<ref name=\"Statewide Totals\"/>\n\n=== 2016 ===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2016#District 2}}\nIn the Republican primary, SImpson defeated perennial candidate [[Lisa Marie]], earning 73% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/results/2016/Primary/statewide_totals.html|title=Statewide Totals|website=www.sos.idaho.gov|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref>\n\nSimpson defeated Jennifer Martinez and Anthony Tomkins in the general election, earning 62.9% of the vote.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sos.idaho.gov/elect/results/2016/General/statewide_totals.html|title=Statewide Totals|website=www.sos.idaho.gov|access-date=2017-04-12}}</ref>\n\n===Election results===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ [[United States House of Representatives elections|U.S. House elections]] ([[Idaho's 2nd congressional district|Idaho's 2nd district]]): Results 1998\u20132014\n!|Year\n!\n!|Democrat\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n!|Republican\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n!|3rd Party\n!|Party\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n!|3rd Party\n!|Party\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n|-\n|1998\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Richard H. Stallings|Richard Stallings]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |77,736\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=center|44.7%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Simpson'''\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |91,337\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=center|52.5%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Jonathan B<!--radford-->. Ratner\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |[[Natural Law Party (United States)|Natural Law]]\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |4,854\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |2.8%\n|\n|-\n|2000\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Craig Williams\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |58,265\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=center|25.9%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Simpson''' (inc.)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |158,912\n|{{Party shad