endent}} align=\"right\" |1.2%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2008#District 2|2008]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Debbie Holmes]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |83,878\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=center|28.9%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Simpson''' (inc.)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |205,777\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=center|70.9%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Gregory Nemitz\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Write-in\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |612\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |0.2%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2010#District 2|2010]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Mike Crawford\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |48,749\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=center|24.4%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Simpson''' (inc.)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |137,468\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=center|68.8%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Brian Schad\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |13,500\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |6.8%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2012#District 2|2012]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Nicole LeFavour]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |110,847\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=center|34.8%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Simpson''' (inc.)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |207,412\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=center|65.1%\n|\n|-\n|[[United States House of Representatives elections in Idaho, 2014#District 2|2014]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Richard H. Stallings|Richard Stallings]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |82,801\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=center|38.6%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Simpson''' (inc.)\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |131,492\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=center|61.4%\n|\n|-\n|}\n\nSource:<ref name=ootcest>{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives|title=Office of the Clerk: Election statistics|accessdate=March 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Larry Craig scandal==\nDuring the 2007 scandal involving Senator [[Larry Craig]] (R-ID), Simpson was openly considered for an appointment to the U.S. Senate in the event that Senator Craig resigned.  Simpson, however, asked Governor [[Butch Otter|C.L. \"Butch\" Otter]] to remove his name from consideration, claiming that the Idaho Congressional Delegation would be in a better position if he were to remain in the House and retain his seniority on the House [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee]].\n\nSimpson rankled Senate leadership during the Craig scandal by criticizing them for their treatment of the Senator. Simpson is quoted as saying, \"If that's how they treat their own, that tells me they're more interested in party than individuals, and the party is made up of individuals. How you treat them says a lot about your party.\"<ref name=\"thehill2007\">{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/leading-the-news/lashing-out-at-mcconnell-2007-09-07.html |title=News Archive |publisher=TheHill.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref> Simpson is not known to have condoned Craig's alleged misconduct, but he demanded that Craig be treated fairly. For example, he is quoted as saying, \"They have people over there [in the Senate Republican Conference] in far worse trouble that they haven't said a thing about.\"<ref name=\"thehill2007\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Idaho's 2nd congressional district]]\n\n==References==\n{{Bioguide}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://simpson.house.gov Congressman Mike Simpson] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.simpsonforcongress.com/ Mike Simpson 